posts.title: I grew up in a small town and didn't realize how much inner city liberals hate us until after I went to college and dealt with them
posts.content:
So this was something I tried to post on Reddit, but it got deleted because they didn't like how I was 'trash talking' people for politics. But it should be fine to post here.

I grew up in a small town farming community, both my parents had college degrees, and they actively made sure I was reading at least one new book a month because education was very important to them. So when I was getting ready to graduate high school, it was very important to them that I go to college.

I went to a community college for two years and honestly I would say that was a quality education because you didn't see a lot of the crazy shit you see on college campuses these days, keep in mind I went to my local community college 2013 to 2015, so none of this woke BS was really going on then.

But then I transferred to a four year university in 2015, and honestly I had never met a bigger group of conceited assholes in my life. I had professors talk down to me thinking I wouldn't be able to understand some of the bigger words because of my background. Only to piss them off when I would show that I could understand what they were talking about.

All they did was complain about how bad 'rednecks' were for the environment and how they were killing the planet. Meanwhile he was sipping out of a new coffee cup from Starbucks everyday. Same professor would always complain about the rich but he drove a fucking Mercedes to school.

Another professor I had for my degree suggested that it was a bad idea to legalize marijuana because 'mInorites who rely on that in impoverished communities would be disenfranchised and wouldn't be able to have a job.' And somehow I was the only one who thought there was something wrong with it, while all the inner city kids are nodding their heads up and down.

One time I did a report on symbolism and social movements for a class. And I made a slideshow with George Lincoln Rockwell and Malcolm X.

And the black students knew who Malcolm X was, but they weren't happy to find out that George Lincoln Rockwell actually agreed with Malcolm X.

After the presentation was done, my professor took me out in the hallway and lectured me saying that I didn't know the damage I could do to them because I was insulting one of their 'cultural' heroes.

And I'm standing there like 'I didn't insult anyone, that quote from George Lincoln Rockwell is true, and he did actually like Elijah Muhammad and Malcolm X.'

This guy absolutely hated me for the rest of the semester and would constantly dock me points. I only passed the class with a D. But above all else, he would constantly make thinly veiled jabs at 'uneducated hillbillies'

And that just pissed me off so much because some of the stuff he lauded as higher education was just basic level knowledge I learned in high school. So I don't understand how this guy could jerk himself off thinking he was so much better than everyone when he didn't even know about some of the stuff I learned in high school

EDIT: Also something additional, growing up we used to love watching Blue Collar comedy tour. But DAMN, don't ever mention you like that on a college campus, because they will treat you like you're Hitler reincarnated. But screw those guys, I still love those specials
